Slide 4 — “Platform Engineering Is Not Just an Internal Capability; It’s a New Services Business”
Frame platform engineering as a monetizable services stack: advisory and maturity assessment, platform build and modernization, and co-managed or managed platform operations. The strongest external proof point here is that 84% of surveyed organizations already partner with external vendors, and co-managed platform models show more developer time going to innovation: 47% versus 38% for fully internally managed platforms. That makes a very strong argument for a tech services company to productize accelerators, golden paths, governance packs, and managed enablement services. Google Cloud Blog Google Cloud ESG report

Slide 5 — “From Ticket-Ops to Productized Platforms: The Operating Model Shift”
Position the change as moving from fragmented DevOps and infrastructure ticket handling to a platform product with clear customer journeys, self-service interfaces, and engineered guardrails. DORA explicitly frames platform engineering as a sociotechnical discipline built around shared workflows, golden paths, and internal developer platforms, while also warning against “ticket-ops” and “ivory tower” behavior. This is a good place to show a before/after operating model graphic: tickets, manual approvals, snowflake pipelines, inconsistent controls on the left; self-service golden paths, embedded policy, reusable capabilities, and clear feedback on the right. DORA CNCF Platforms White Paper

Slide 6 — “Golden Paths + Internal Developer Platform = The Commercialization Layer”
This slide should explain how platform engineering becomes tangible. Red Hat’s framing is useful: golden paths are opinionated, well-documented, supported ways of building and deploying software. They improve consistency, automation, speed, security, and reduce cognitive load. Pair that with the CNCF message that platforms should be secure-by-default, self-service, and composable. For a tech services audience, the message is: the service offering is not “we run Kubernetes for you”; it is “we give your engineering teams a reusable, governed path to deliver software faster.” Red Hat CNCF Platforms White Paper

Slide 7 — “A Leadership Roadmap: From Provisional to Optimizing Platform Maturity”
Use the CNCF maturity model as the core visual. Show the four stages — Provisional, Operationalized, Scalable, Optimizing — across five dimensions: staff/funding, adoption, interfaces, operations, and feedback. The executive takeaway should be that the goal is not just better tooling; it is moving from temporary, reactive teams and manual processes to a product-managed platform with intrinsic adoption, self-service, centralized orchestration, and data-driven improvement. This works well as a transformation roadmap with a “where are we now / where do we want to be in 12–24 months” overlay. CNCF Maturity Model

Slide 8 — “Why AI Raises the Stakes: Platform Quality Determines Whether AI Creates Value or Chaos”
This is one of the strongest strategic slides. DORA’s finding is especially compelling: when platform quality is high, the effect of AI adoption on organizational performance becomes strongly positive; when platform quality is low, the benefit is negligible. Google Cloud/ESG adds that 86% of respondents believe platform engineering is essential to realizing AI business value, and 94% say AI is critical or important to the future of platform engineering. This lets you make a sharp executive point: AI without platform engineering accelerates local coding output but can still create downstream disorder in testing, security, deployment, and compliance. DORA Google Cloud Blog

Slide 9 — “What Leaders Should Measure: A Platform Value Scorecard”
Recommend a balanced scorecard with four lenses. First, software delivery: lead time, deployment frequency, change failure rate, and recovery time. Second, developer experience: adoption, CSAT/NPS, task success, and independence. Third, economics: cloud cost efficiency, reuse rate, automation rate, and platform cost-to-serve. Fourth, risk/compliance: policy compliance, auditability, vulnerability remediation, and template standardization. This slide can connect back to your Shell deck’s OKRs while expanding them with DORA and DevEx measures. It also answers a major market gap, because 29.6% of platform teams reportedly still do not measure success at all. DORA PlatformEngineering.org

Slide 10 — “Three Failure Modes to Avoid”
This should be a pragmatic anti-patterns slide. DORA gives you an excellent set: “build it and they will come,” “ivory tower,” and “ticket-ops.” Add the “big bang platform” risk from DORA and the “one-size-fits-all” problem, especially since 55.9% of companies now operate more than one platform. The executive takeaway: successful programs start with one or two high-friction journeys, build a minimum viable platform, prove adoption, and expand through reusable capabilities rather than through central mandates alone. DORA PlatformEngineering.org

Slide 11 — “The Recommended Executive Decision: Start with a 90-Day Platform Engineering Wedge”
This should end with a concrete ask. I’d suggest a phased CTA: first 30 days for maturity assessment and value-stream diagnosis; days 31–60 to define the platform product scope, target personas, golden paths, and KPI baseline; days 61–90 to deliver a minimum viable platform for one priority journey such as service bootstrap, environment provisioning, or secure CI/CD. Thoughtworks supports this incremental approach and provides a strong proof point with a financial services client that reduced deployment time from three weeks to 15 minutes by treating the platform as a product and building reusable capabilities. Thoughtworks

A few research points are especially strong and worth making visually prominent in the final deck: 55% adoption, 90% expansion intent, 85% developer reliance, only 27% of adopters having fully integrated collaboration + platform-as-product + metrics, 84% partnering with external vendors, 47% innovation time in co-managed models, 86% saying platform engineering is essential for AI value, and DORA’s point that developer independence improved productivity by 5%. Google Cloud Blog Google Cloud ESG report DORA Google Cloud Blog

